metadata.name: The Symphony of the Ether #5
metadata.description:
Once upon a time, in a digital realm called the Ether, there lived a group of circles and lines. These shapes were unlike any other, for they had the ability to generate art all on their own.

The circles were a vibrant and lively bunch, always spinning and dancing about, while the lines were more reserved, preferring to stay in place and hold their ground. Despite their differences, the circles and lines worked together seamlessly, creating beautiful and intricate compositions.

One day, the shapes decided to use a special library called RoughJS to add an element of randomness to their creations. With RoughJS, the circles and lines were able to create even more unique and varied works of art.

As the shapes continued to generate art, their compositions became more and more complex. They began to resemble musical notes, with the circles representing the round and flowing melody, and the lines representing the strong and steady beat.

The art that the circles and lines created was so beautiful and mesmerizing that it became known as the Ethernal Notes. And as the shapes continued to generate these ethereal compositions, they became a source of inspiration and joy for all who viewed them.

The end. ;)

In live mode click "s" to save image (2200 x 3030).

+---+
The Symphony of the Ether by __Reiji_c
+---+
Made with vanilla javascript + (roughjs MIT License (c) Preet Shihn)

metadata.name: 山水畫 #123
metadata.description:
山水, literally mountain and water, i.e. landscape. Instead ink, brush, and rice paper, rectangles, p5js and screen, explores not code realism, but code-ism composition and form. 畫, painting, each landscape is performed, unknowing the exact, as is Chinese landscape painting, the painter, paints his or her fictional landscape. Here my code and the hash paints each landscape with a constrained brush, that is rectangles. 

An important aesthetic factor in Chinese landscape painting is the negative space. Here the positive-negative relation is akin to ying-yang, that in Tai-Chi (太極), there are no absolute positive-yang and absolute negative-ying. At the edge of one polar extreme, signals the change towards the other. Like midday, the sun will set. And between midday and midnight, there is plenty of grey. 

I am sorry “life has no scores” will not be my final drop just yet. Precisely since life has no fixed scores to follow. In preparation for my solo ink show in march, I look towards generative art to give me inspiration. Instead of code imitating brush, my brush and mind aims to discover my own fictional landscapes through code and hashes. 

To see mountains, where there are not any, just the concept of them. I hope you enjoy the mountain view as I will. fxhash is more than a community, when our path crosses, we create art together.  

Press ‘2’ to save png.

Tested on chrome, preview images might be compressed.

metadata.name: Fantasized Telekinetic Obliteration #5
metadata.description:
An exploration on the ways in which mental energy might be captured and converted to kinetic destruction.

Each piece begins with an abstract shape. The shape is subjected to a field of disruptors, which contains a combination of beams and bombs. Beams slice through material, shearing fragments generally in the direction the beam is traveling. Bombs shatter material apart and eject shards away from the blast site.

All matter is conserved. That is, if the exploded and scattered fragments were reverted back to their initial positions, there would be a fully intact shape. No virtual particles. 🖤

Some structures may be annihilated. Others may take minor damage — or perhaps, none at all. Consult the “telekinetic power” feature for a full assessment.

---
- made with p5js
- press “s” to save png

metadata.name: Oscillators #134
metadata.description:
Click anywhere on the oscillator to play/pause.

3 Rules of Oscillators:
RULE 1, Oscillators should be viewed on Desktop (this is due to the way an oscillator is formed, it requires the display density of the device to be 2 pixels).
RULE 2, Oscillators should be viewed live and not as static images.
RULE 3, Oscillators should be run with the sound on.

Press "S" to Save a version of the Canvas (must be in fullscreen mode)

You are in a dark cave in the Johto region, the year is 1999...

Two synthesizers play a graceful melody atop the shimmering sound of a french horn. A cello provides a deep and haunting counterpoint.

Created with Tone.js and p5js.

Thank you to https://github.com/nbrosowsky/tonejs-instruments for the french horn and cello samples.

metadata.name: PARIS #89
metadata.description:
Paris is a generative and animated piece creating shapes based on trails. 
The size, position and motion frequency of each circles are generated for each token, along with the color theme. 

Each reloading creates a different movement, as the algorithm underlying the piece is partially based on a noise.
At the end, the animation stop and the visual is created.

Created by Quentin Hocdé, in La-Roche-Neuville (France).

metadata.name: Mines #73
metadata.description:
"He found himself wondering at times, especially in the autumn, about the wild lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his dreams"
- J.R.R. Tolkien

Mines is an exploration of these mountains of dreams, and the ancient mechanics that shape them. The work of eons, where the landscapes we know rise and fall like ocean waves.

To know them, we must go beneath the mountain.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press “s” to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at specific width
- Use param ?bg=true to render on full color background (instead of the default dark background)

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #269
metadata.description:
“Ordinary Places” is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher’s “Water Tower” photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha’s “26 Gasoline Stations” photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather’s farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: The Likeness of a Flower #178
metadata.description:
And the unseen eyebeam crossed, for the roses
Had the look of flowers that are looked at.
- T.S. Eliot, Four Quartets: Burnt Norton (1936)

This work is an attempt to encapsulate in an algorithm, not the likeness of a flower, but the likeness of a painting of a flower. If, according to a very old definition, art is an imitation of nature, this is an imitation of an imitation – a sort of meta-imitation of nature by means of computer code.

The challenge for this piece was to capture some of the looseness and fluidity of the human hand when holding a brush or a pencil, and reproducing some typical forms of hand-made scribbles, doodles and brush strokes. However, absent the materiality of paint and canvas, everything is simulated here on the base of a very simple resource: circles. Everything you see is built of very many overlapping circles of varying sizes, colors and opacities. It is circles all the way down…

Inspiration for this work comes from a number of expressionist painters, from 20th century classics like Cy Twombly, to the magnificent contemporary work of Philip Maltman: https://www.instagram.com/philipmaltman/

This work is animated.
Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 1000 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be slow.

Made with the open-source libraries p5.js and chroma.js
